# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: mediapipe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The scientific discipline of computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, multi-dimensional data from a 3D scanner, 3D point clouds from LiDaR sensors, or medical scanning devices.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The technological discipline of computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models to the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Subdisciplines of computer vision include scene reconstruction, object detection, event detection, activity recognition, video tracking, object recognition, 3D pose estimation, learning, indexing, motion estimation, visual servoing, 3D scene modeling, and image restoration.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Computer vision is an interdisciplinary field that deals with how computers can be made to gain high-level understanding from digital images or videos.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] From the perspective of engineering, it seeks to automate tasks that the human visual system can do.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] "Computer vision is concerned with the automatic extraction, analysis, and understanding of useful information from a single image or a sequence of images.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] It involves the development of a theoretical and algorithmic basis to achieve automatic visual understanding." As a scientific discipline, computer vision is concerned with the theory behind artificial systems that extract information from images.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The image data can take many forms, such as video sequences, views from multiple cameras, or multi-dimensional data from a medical scanner.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] As a technological discipline, computer vision seeks to apply its theories and models for the construction of computer vision systems.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Machine vision refers to a systems engineering discipline, especially in the context of factory automation.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] In more recent times, the terms computer vision and machine vision have converged to a greater degree.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] In the late 1960s, computer vision began at universities that were pioneering artificial intelligence.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] It was meant to mimic the human visual system as a stepping stone to endowing robots with intelligent behavior.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] In 1966, it was believed that this could be achieved through an undergraduate summer project, by attaching a camera to a computer and having it "describe what it saw".
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] What distinguished computer vision from the prevalent field of digital image processing at that time was a desire to extract three-dimensional structure from images with the goal of achieving full scene understanding.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The next decade saw studies based on more rigorous mathematical analysis and quantitative aspects of computer vision.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] These include the concept of scale-space, the inference of shape from various cues such as shading, texture and focus, and contour models known as snakes.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Researchers also realized that many of these mathematical concepts could be treated within the same optimization framework as regularization and Markov random fields.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] By the 1990s, some of the previous research topics became more active than others.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Research in projective 3-D reconstructions led to better understanding of camera calibration.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] With the advent of optimization methods for camera calibration, it was realized that a lot of the ideas were already explored in bundle adjustment theory from the field of photogrammetry.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] This led to methods for sparse 3-D reconstructions of scenes from multiple images.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Progress was made on the dense stereo correspondence problem and further multi-view stereo techniques.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] At the same time, variations of graph cut were used to solve image segmentation.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] This decade also marked the first time statistical learning techniques were used in practice to recognize faces in images (see Eigenface).
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Toward the end of the 1990s, a significant change came about with the increased interaction between the fields of computer graphics and computer vision.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] This included image-based rendering, image morphing, view interpolation, panoramic image stitching and early light-field rendering.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Recent work has seen the resurgence of feature-based methods used in conjunction with machine learning techniques and complex optimization frameworks.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The advancement of Deep Learning techniques has brought further life to the field of computer vision.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The accuracy of deep learning algorithms on several benchmark computer vision data sets for tasks ranging from classification, segmentation and optical flow has surpassed prior methods.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Solid-state physics is another field that is closely related to computer vision.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems rely on image sensors, which detect electromagnetic radiation, which is typically in the form of either visible, infrared or ultraviolet light.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The sensors are designed using quantum physics.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The process by which light interacts with surfaces is explained using physics.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Physics explains the behavior of optics which are a core part of most imaging systems.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Sophisticated image sensors even require quantum mechanics to provide a complete understanding of the image formation process.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Also, various measurement problems in physics can be addressed using computer vision, for example, motion in fluids.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The starfish match with a ringed texture and a star outline, whereas most sea urchins match with a striped texture and oval shape.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] However, the instance of a ring-textured sea urchin creates a weakly weighted association between them.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The network correctly detects the starfish.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] However, the weakly weighted association between ringed texture and sea urchin also confers a weak signal to the latter from one of two intermediate nodes.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] In addition, a shell that was not included in the training gives a weak signal for the oval shape, also resulting in a weak signal for the sea urchin output.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] In reality, textures and outlines would not be represented by single nodes, but rather by associated weight patterns of multiple nodes.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Neurobiology has greatly influenced the development of computer vision algorithms.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Over the last century, there has been an extensive study of eyes, neurons, and brain structures devoted to the processing of visual stimuli in both humans and various animals.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] This has led to a coarse yet convoluted description of how natural vision systems operate in order to solve certain vision-related tasks.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] These results have led to a sub-field within computer vision where artificial systems are designed to mimic the processing and behavior of biological systems at different levels of complexity.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Also, some of the learning-based methods developed within computer vision (*e.g.* neural net and deep learning based image and feature analysis and classification) have their background in neurobiology.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The Neocognitron, a neural network developed in the 1970s by Kunihiko Fukushima, is an early example of computer vision taking direct inspiration from neurobiology, specifically the primary visual cortex.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Some strands of computer vision research are closely related to the study of biological vision—indeed, just as many strands of AI research are closely tied with research into human intelligence and the use of stored knowledge to interpret, integrate, and utilize visual information.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The field of biological vision studies and models the physiological processes behind visual perception in humans and other animals.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Computer vision, on the other hand, develops and describes the algorithms implemented in software and hardware behind artificial vision systems.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] An interdisciplinary exchange between biological and computer vision has proven fruitful for both fields.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Yet another field related to computer vision is signal processing.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Many methods for processing one-variable signals, typically temporal signals, can be extended in a natural way to the processing of two-variable signals or multi-variable signals in computer vision.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] However, because of the specific nature of images, there are many methods developed within computer vision that have no counterpart in the processing of one-variable signals.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Together with the multi-dimensionality of the signal, this defines a subfield in signal processing as a part of computer vision.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Robot navigation sometimes deals with autonomous path planning or deliberation for robotic systems to navigate through an environment.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] A detailed understanding of these environments is required to navigate through them.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Visual computing is a generic term for all computer science disciplines dealing with images and 3D models, such as computer graphics, image processing, visualization, computer vision, virtual and augmented reality, video processing, and computational visualistics.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes aspects of pattern recognition, human computer interaction, machine learning and digital libraries.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The core challenges are the acquisition, processing, analysis and rendering of visual information (mainly images and video).
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Application areas include industrial quality control, medical image processing and visualization, surveying, robotics, multimedia systems, virtual heritage, special effects in movies and television, and ludology.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Visual computing also includes digital art and digital media studies.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Besides the above-mentioned views on computer vision, many of the related research topics can also be studied from a purely mathematical point of view.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] For example, many methods in computer vision are based on statistics, optimization or geometry.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Finally, a significant part of the field is devoted to the implementation aspect of computer vision; how existing methods can be realized in various combinations of software and hardware, or how these methods can be modified in order to gain processing speed without losing too much performance.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Computer vision is also used in fashion eCommerce, inventory management, patent search, furniture, and the beauty industry.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The fields most closely related to computer vision are image processing, image analysis and machine vision.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] There is a significant overlap in the range of techniques and applications that these cover.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] This implies that the basic techniques that are used and developed in these fields are similar, something which can be interpreted as there is only one field with different names.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] In image processing, the input and output are both images, whereas in computer vision, the input is an image or video, and the output could be an enhanced image, an analysis of the image's content, or even a system's behavior based on that analysis.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Computer graphics produces image data from 3D models, and computer vision often produces 3D models from image data.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] There is also a trend towards a combination of the two disciplines, *e.g.*, as explored in augmented reality.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Photogrammetry also overlaps with computer vision, e.g., stereophotogrammetry vs. computer stereo vision.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Applications range from tasks such as industrial machine vision systems which, say, inspect bottles speeding by on a production line, to research into artificial intelligence and computers or robots that can comprehend the world around them.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The computer vision and machine vision fields have significant overlap.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Computer vision covers the core technology of automated image analysis which is used in many fields.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Machine vision usually refers to a process of combining automated image analysis with other methods and technologies to provide automated inspection and robot guidance in industrial applications.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] In many computer-vision applications, computers are pre-programmed to solve a particular task, but methods based on learning are now becoming increasingly common.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] For 2024, the leading areas of computer vision were industry (market size US$5.22 billion), medicine (market size US$2.6 billion), military (market size US$996.2 million).
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] One of the most prominent application fields is medical computer vision, or medical image processing, characterized by the extraction of information from image data to diagnose a patient.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] An example of this is the detection of tumours, arteriosclerosis or other malign changes, and a variety of dental pathologies; measurements of organ dimensions, blood flow, etc. are another example.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] It also supports medical research by providing new information: *e.g.*, about the structure of the brain or the quality of medical treatments.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Applications of computer vision in the medical area also include enhancement of images interpreted by humans—ultrasonic images or X-ray images, for example—to reduce the influence of noise.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] A second application area in computer vision is in industry, sometimes called machine vision, where information is extracted for the purpose of supporting a production process.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] One example is quality control where details or final products are being automatically inspected in order to find defects.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] One of the most prevalent fields for such inspecti is the Wafer industry in which every single Wafer is being measured and inspected for inaccuracies or defects to prevent a computer chip from coming to market in an unusable manner.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Another example is a measurement of the position and orientation of details to be picked up by a robot arm.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Machine vision is also heavily used in the agricultural processes to remove undesirable foodstuff from bulk material, a process called optical sorting.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The obvious examples are the detection of enemy soldiers or vehicles and missile guidance.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] More advanced systems for missile guidance send the missile to an area rather than a specific target, and target selection is made when the missile reaches the area based on locally acquired image data.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Modern military concepts, such as "battlefield awareness", imply that various sensors, including image sensors, provide a rich set of information about a combat scene that can be used to support strategic decisions.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] In this case, automatic processing of the data is used to reduce complexity and to fuse information from multiple sensors to increase reliability.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] One of the newer application areas is autonomous vehicles, which include submersibles, land-based vehicles (small robots with wheels, cars, or trucks), aerial vehicles, and unmanned aerial vehicles (UAV).
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The level of autonomy ranges from fully autonomous (unmanned) vehicles to vehicles where computer-vision-based systems support a driver or a pilot in various situations.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Fully autonomous vehicles typically use computer vision for navigation, e.g., for knowing where they are or mapping their environment (SLAM), for detecting obstacles.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] It can also be used for detecting certain task-specific events, *e.g.*, a UAV looking for forest fires.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Examples of supporting systems are obstacle warning systems in cars, cameras and LiDAR sensors in vehicles, and systems for autonomous landing of aircraft.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Several car manufacturers have demonstrated systems for autonomous driving of cars.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] There are ample examples of military autonomous vehicles ranging from advanced missiles to UAVs for recon missions or missile guidance.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Space exploration is already being made with autonomous vehicles using computer vision, *e.g.*, NASA's *Curiosity* and CNSA's *Yutu-2* rover.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Materials such as rubber and silicon are being used to create sensors that allow for applications such as detecting microundulations and calibrating robotic hands.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Rubber can be used in order to create a mold that can be placed over a finger, inside of this mold would be multiple strain gauges.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The finger mold and sensors could then be placed on top of a small sheet of rubber containing an array of rubber pins.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] A user can then wear the finger mold and trace a surface.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] A computer can then read the data from the strain gauges and measure if one or more of the pins are being pushed upward.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] If a pin is being pushed upward then the computer can recognize this as an imperfection in the surface.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] This sort of technology is useful in order to receive accurate data on imperfections on a very large surface.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Another variation of this finger mold sensor are sensors that contain a camera suspended in silicon.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The silicon forms a dome around the outside of the camera and embedded in the silicon are point markers that are equally spaced.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] These cameras can then be placed on devices such as robotic hands in order to allow the computer to receive highly accurate tactile data.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Each of the application areas described above employ a range of computer vision tasks; more or less well-defined measurement problems or processing problems, which can be solved using a variety of methods.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Some examples of typical computer vision tasks are presented below.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Computer vision tasks include methods for acquiring, processing, analyzing and understanding digital images, and extraction of high-dimensional data from the real world in order to produce numerical or symbolic information, *e.g.*, in the forms of decisions.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Understanding in this context means the transformation of visual images into descriptions of the world that can interface with other thought processes and elicit appropriate action.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] This image understanding can be seen as the disentangling of symbolic information from image data using models constructed with the aid of geometry, physics, statistics, and learning theory.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The classical problem in computer vision, image processing, and machine vision is that of determining whether or not the image data contains some specific object, feature, or activity.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Different varieties of recognition problem are described in the literature.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Currently, the best algorithms for such tasks are based on convolutional neural networks.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] An illustration of their capabilities is given by the ImageNet Large Scale Visual Recognition Challenge; this is a benchmark in object classification and detection, with millions of images and 1000 object classes used in the competition.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Performance of convolutional neural networks on the ImageNet tests is now close to that of humans.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The best algorithms still struggle with objects that are small or thin, such as a small ant on the stem of a flower or a person holding a quill in their hand.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] They also have trouble with images that have been distorted with filters (an increasingly common phenomenon with modern digital cameras).
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] By contrast, those kinds of images rarely trouble humans.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Humans, however, tend to have trouble with other issues.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] For example, they are not good at classifying objects into fine-grained classes, such as the particular breed of dog or species of bird, whereas convolutional neural networks handle this with ease.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Several tasks relate to motion estimation, where an image sequence is processed to produce an estimate of the velocity either at each points in the image or in the 3D scene or even of the camera that produces the images.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Given one or (typically) more images of a scene, or a video, scene reconstruction aims at computing a 3D model of the scene.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] In the simplest case, the model can be a set of 3D points.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods produce a complete 3D surface model.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The advent of 3D imaging not requiring motion or scanning, and related processing algorithms is enabling rapid advances in this field.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Grid-based 3D sensing can be used to acquire 3D images from multiple angles.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Algorithms are now available to stitch multiple 3D images together into point clouds and 3D models.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Image restoration comes into the picture when the original image is degraded or damaged due to some external factors like lens wrong positioning, transmission interference, low lighting or motion blurs, etc., which is referred to as noise.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] When the images are degraded or damaged, the information to be extracted from them also gets damaged.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Therefore, we need to recover or restore the image as it was intended to be.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The aim of image restoration is the removal of noise (sensor noise, motion blur, etc.) from images.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The simplest possible approach for noise removal is various types of filters, such as low-pass filters or median filters.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] More sophisticated methods assume a model of how the local image structures look to distinguish them from noise.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] By first analyzing the image data in terms of the local image structures, such as lines or edges, and then controlling the filtering based on local information from the analysis step, a better level of noise removal is usually obtained compared to the simpler approaches.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The organization of a computer vision system is highly application-dependent.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Some systems are stand-alone applications that solve a specific measurement or detection problem, while others constitute a sub-system of a larger design which, for example, also contains sub-systems for control of mechanical actuators, planning, information databases, man-machine interfaces, etc.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The specific implementation of a computer vision system also depends on whether its functionality is pre-specified or if some part of it can be learned or modified during operation.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Many functions are unique to the application.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] There are, however, typical functions that are found in many computer vision systems.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] More complex features may be related to texture, shape, or motion.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Image-understanding systems (IUS) include three levels of abstraction as follows: low level includes image primitives such as edges, texture elements, or regions; intermediate level includes boundaries, surfaces and volumes; and high level includes objects, scenes, or events.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Many of these requirements are entirely topics for further research.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] The representational requirements in the designing of IUS for these levels are: representation of prototypical concepts, concept organization, spatial knowledge, temporal knowledge, scaling, and description by comparison and differentiation.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] While inference refers to the process of deriving new, not explicitly represented facts from currently known facts, control refers to the process that selects which of the many inference, search, and matching techniques should be applied at a particular stage of processing.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Inference and control requirements for IUS are: search and hypothesis activation, matching and hypothesis testing, generation and use of expectations, change and focus of attention, certainty and strength of belief, inference and goal satisfaction.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] There are many kinds of computer vision systems; however, all of them contain these basic elements: a power source, at least one image acquisition device (camera, ccd, etc.), a processor, and control and communication cables or some kind of wireless interconnection mechanism.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] In addition, a practical vision system contains software, as well as a display in order to monitor the system.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Vision systems for inner spaces, as most industrial ones, contain an illumination system and may be placed in a controlled environment.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Furthermore, a completed system includes many accessories, such as camera supports, cables, and connectors.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Most computer vision systems use visible-light cameras passively viewing a scene at frame rates of at most 60 frames per second (usually far slower).
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Such hardware captures "images" that are then processed often using the same computer vision algorithms used to process visible-light images.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] For applications in robotics, fast, real-time video systems are critically important and often can simplify the processing needed for certain algorithms.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] When combined with a high-speed projector, fast image acquisition allows 3D measurement and feature tracking to be realized.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] Egocentric vision systems are composed of a wearable camera that automatically take pictures from a first-person perspective.
[src:mediapipe/computer-vision] As of 2016, vision processing units are emerging as a new class of processors to complement CPUs and graphics processing units (GPUs) in this role.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:mediapipe/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] A **facial recognition system** is a technology potentially capable of matching a human face from a digital image or a video frame against a database of faces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Such a system is typically employed to authenticate users through ID verification services, and works by pinpointing and measuring facial features from a given image.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Development on similar systems began in the 1960s as a form of computer application.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Since their inception, facial recognition systems have seen wider uses in recent times on smartphones and in other forms of technology, such as robotics.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Because computerized facial recognition involves the measurement of a human's physiological characteristics, facial recognition systems are categorized as biometrics.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Although the accuracy of facial recognition systems as a biometric technology is lower than iris recognition, fingerprint image acquisition, palm recognition or voice recognition, it is widely adopted due to its contactless process.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Facial recognition systems have been deployed in advanced human–computer interaction, video surveillance, law enforcement, passenger screening, decisions on employment and housing, and automatic indexing of images.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Facial recognition systems are employed throughout the world today by governments and private companies.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Their effectiveness varies, and some systems have previously been scrapped because of their ineffectiveness.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The use of facial recognition systems has also raised controversy, with claims that the systems violate citizens' privacy, commonly make incorrect identifications, encourage gender norms and racial profiling, and do not protect important biometric data.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The appearance of synthetic media such as deepfakes has also raised concerns about its security.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] These claims have led to the ban of facial recognition systems in several cities in the United States.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Growing societal concerns led social networking company Meta Platforms to shut down its Facebook facial recognition system in 2021, deleting the face-scan data of more than one billion users.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The change represented one of the largest shifts in facial recognition usage in the technology's history.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] IBM also stopped offering facial recognition technology due to similar concerns.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Automated facial recognition was pioneered in the 1960s by Woody Bledsoe, Helen Chan Wolf, and Charles Bisson, whose work focused on teaching computers to recognize human faces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Their early facial recognition project was dubbed "man-machine" because a human first needed to establish the coordinates of facial features in a photograph before they could be used by a computer for recognition.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Using a graphics tablet, a human would pinpoint facial features coordinates, such as the pupil centers, the inside and outside corners of eyes, and the widows peak in the hairline.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The coordinates were used to calculate 20 individual distances, including the width of the mouth and of the eyes.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] A human could process about 40 pictures an hour, building a database of these computed distances.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] A computer would then automatically compare the distances for each photograph, calculate the difference between the distances, and return the closed records as a possible match.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 1970, Takeo Kanade publicly demonstrated a face-matching system that located anatomical features such as the chin and calculated the distance ratio between facial features without human intervention.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Later tests revealed that the system could not always reliably identify facial features.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Nonetheless, interest in the subject grew and in 1977 Kanade published the first detailed book on facial recognition technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The FERET tests found that while the performance of existing automated facial recognition systems varied, a handful of existing methods could viably be used to recognize faces in still images taken in a controlled environment.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The FERET tests spawned three US companies that sold automated facial recognition systems.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Vision Corporation and Miros Inc were founded in 1994, by researchers who used the results of the FERET tests as a selling point.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Viisage Technology was established by an identification card defense contractor in 1996 to commercially exploit the rights to the facial recognition algorithm developed by Alex Pentland at MIT.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Following the 1993 FERET face-recognition vendor test, the Department of Motor Vehicles (DMV) offices in West Virginia and New Mexico became the first DMV offices to use automated facial recognition systems to prevent people from obtaining multiple driving licenses using different names.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Driver's licenses in the United States were at that point a commonly accepted form of photo identification.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] DMV offices across the United States were undergoing a technological upgrade and were in the process of establishing databases of digital ID photographs.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] This enabled DMV offices to deploy the facial recognition systems on the market to search photographs for new driving licenses against the existing DMV database.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] DMV offices became one of the first major markets for automated facial recognition technology and introduced US citizens to facial recognition as a standard method of identification.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The increase of the US prison population in the 1990s prompted U.S. states to established connected and automated identification systems that incorporated digital biometric databases, in some instances this included facial recognition.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 1999, Minnesota incorporated the facial recognition system FaceIT by Visionics into a mug shot booking system that allowed police, judges and court officers to track criminals across the state.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Until the 1990s, facial recognition systems were developed primarily by using photographic portraits of human faces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Research on face recognition to reliably locate a face in an image that contains other objects gained traction in the early 1990s with the principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The PCA method of face detection is also known as Eigenface and was developed by Matthew Turk and Alex Pentland.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Turk and Pentland combined the conceptual approach of the Karhunen–Loève theorem and factor analysis, to develop a linear model.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Eigenfaces are determined based on global and orthogonal features in human faces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] A human face is calculated as a weighted combination of a number of Eigenfaces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Because few Eigenfaces were used to encode human faces of a given population, Turk and Pentland's PCA face detection method greatly reduced the amount of data that had to be processed to detect a face.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Pentland in 1994 defined Eigenface features, including eigen eyes, eigen mouths and eigen noses, to advance the use of PCA in facial recognition.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 1997, the PCA Eigenface method of face recognition was improved upon using linear discriminant analysis (LDA) to produce Fisherfaces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] LDA Fisherfaces became dominantly used in PCA feature based face recognition.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] While Eigenfaces were also used for face reconstruction.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In these approaches no global structure of the face is calculated which links the facial features or parts.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Purely feature based approaches to facial recognition were overtaken in the late 1990s by the Bochum system, which used Gabor filter to record the face features and computed a grid of the face structure to link the features.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Christoph von der Malsburg and his research team at the University of Bochum developed Elastic Bunch Graph Matching in the mid-1990s to extract a face out of an image using skin segmentation.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] By 1997, the face detection method developed by Malsburg outperformed most other facial detection systems on the market.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The so-called "Bochum system" of face detection was sold commercially on the market as ZN-Face to operators of airports and other busy locations.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The software was "robust enough to make identifications from less-than-perfect face views.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] It can also often see through such impediments to identification as mustaches, beards, changed hairstyles and glasses—even sunglasses".
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Real-time face detection in video footage became possible in 2001 with the Viola–Jones object detection framework for faces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Paul Viola and Michael Jones combined their face detection method with the Haar-like feature approach to object recognition in digital images to launch AdaBoost, the first real-time frontal-view face detector.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] By 2015, the Viola–Jones algorithm had been implemented using small low power detectors on handheld devices and embedded systems.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Therefore, the Viola–Jones algorithm has not only broadened the practical application of face recognition systems but has also been used to support new features in user interfaces and teleconferencing.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Ukraine is using the US-based Clearview AI facial recognition software to identify dead Russian soldiers.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Ukraine has conducted 8,600 searches and identified the families of 582 deceased Russian soldiers.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The IT volunteer section of the Ukrainian army using the software is subsequently contacting the families of the deceased soldiers to raise awareness of Russian activities in Ukraine.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The main goal is to destabilise the Russian government.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] It can be seen as a form of psychological warfare.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] About 340 Ukrainian government officials in five government ministries are using the technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] It is used to catch spies that might try to enter Ukraine.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Clearview AI's facial recognition database is only available to government agencies who may only use the technology to assist in the course of law enforcement investigations or in connection with national security.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The software was donated to Ukraine by Clearview AI.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Russia is thought to be using it to find anti-war activists.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Clearview AI was originally designed for US law enforcement.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Using it in war raises new ethical concerns.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] One London based surveillance expert, Stephen Hare, is concerned it might make the Ukrainians appear inhuman: "Is it actually working?
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] While humans can recognize faces without much effort, facial recognition is a challenging pattern recognition problem in computing.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Facial recognition systems attempt to identify a human face, which is three-dimensional and changes in appearance with lighting and facial expression, based on its two-dimensional image.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] To accomplish this computational task, facial recognition systems perform four steps.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] First face detection is used to segment the face from the image background.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In the second step the segmented face image is aligned to account for face pose, image size and photographic properties, such as illumination and grayscale.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The purpose of the alignment process is to enable the accurate localization of facial features in the third step, the facial feature extraction.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Features such as eyes, nose and mouth are pinpointed and measured in the image to represent the face.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The so established feature vector of the face is then, in the fourth step, matched against a database of faces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Some face recognition algorithms identify facial features by extracting landmarks, or features, from an image of the subject's face.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] For example, an algorithm may analyze the relative position, size, and/or shape of the eyes, nose, cheekbones, and jaw.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] These features are then used to search for other images with matching features.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Other algorithms normalize a gallery of face images and then compress the face data, only saving the data in the image that is useful for face recognition.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] A probe image is then compared with the face data.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] One of the earliest successful systems is based on template matching techniques applied to a set of salient facial features, providing a sort of compressed face representation.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Recognition algorithms can be divided into two main approaches: geometric, which looks at distinguishing features, or photo-metric, which is a statistical approach that distills an image into values and compares the values with templates to eliminate variances.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Some classify these algorithms into two broad categories: holistic and feature-based models.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The former attempts to recognize the face in its entirety while the feature-based subdivide into components such as according to features and analyze each as well as its spatial location with respect to other features.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Modern facial recognition systems make increasing use of machine learning techniques such as deep learning.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] To enable human identification at a distance (HID) low-resolution images of faces are enhanced using face hallucination.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In CCTV imagery faces are often very small.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] But because facial recognition algorithms that identify and plot facial features require high resolution images, resolution enhancement techniques have been developed to enable facial recognition systems to work with imagery that has been captured in environments with a high signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Use of face hallucination techniques improves the performance of high resolution facial recognition algorithms and may be used to overcome the inherent limitations of super-resolution algorithms.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Face hallucination techniques are also used to pre-treat imagery where faces are disguised.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Here the disguise, such as sunglasses, is removed and the face hallucination algorithm is applied to the image.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Such face hallucination algorithms need to be trained on similar face images with and without disguise.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] To fill in the area uncovered by removing the disguise, face hallucination algorithms need to correctly map the entire state of the face, which may be not possible due to the momentary facial expression captured in the low resolution image.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Three-dimensional face recognition technique uses 3D sensors to capture information about the shape of a face.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] This information is then used to identify distinctive features on the surface of a face, such as the contour of the eye sockets, nose, and chin.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] One advantage of 3D face recognition is that it is not affected by changes in lighting like other techniques.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] It can also identify a face from a range of viewing angles, including a profile view.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Three-dimensional data points from a face vastly improve the precision of face recognition.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] 3D-dimensional face recognition research is enabled by the development of sophisticated sensors that project structured light onto the face.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] 3D matching technique are sensitive to expressions, therefore researchers at Technion applied tools from metric geometry to treat expressions as isometries.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] A new method of capturing 3D images of faces uses three tracking cameras that point at different angles; one camera will be pointing at the front of the subject, second one to the side, and third one at an angle.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] All these cameras will work together so it can track a subject's face in real-time and be able to face detect and recognize.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] A different form of taking input data for face recognition is by using thermal cameras, by this procedure the cameras will only detect the shape of the head and it will ignore the subject accessories such as glasses, hats, or makeup.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Unlike conventional cameras, thermal cameras can capture facial imagery even in low-light and nighttime conditions without using a flash and exposing the position of the camera.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] However, the databases for face recognition are limited.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Efforts to build databases of thermal face images date back to 2004.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] By 2016, several databases existed, including the IIITD-PSE and the Notre Dame thermal face database.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Current thermal face recognition systems are not able to reliably detect a face in a thermal image that has been taken of an outdoor environment.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Army Research Laboratory (ARL) developed a technique that would allow them to match facial imagery obtained using a thermal camera with those in databases that were captured using a conventional camera.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Known as a cross-spectrum synthesis method due to how it bridges facial recognition from two different imaging modalities, this method synthesize a single image by analyzing multiple facial regions and details.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] It consists of a non-linear regression model that maps a specific thermal image into a corresponding visible facial image and an optimization issue that projects the latent projection back into the image space.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] ARL scientists have noted that the approach works by combining global information (i.e. features across the entire face) with local information (i.e. features regarding the eyes, nose, and mouth).
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] According to performance tests conducted at ARL, the multi-region cross-spectrum synthesis model demonstrated a performance improvement of about 30% over baseline methods and about 5% over state-of-the-art methods.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Founded in 2013, Looksery went on to raise money for its face modification app on Kickstarter.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] After successful crowdfunding, Looksery launched in October 2014.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The application allows video chat with others through a special filter for faces that modifies the look of users.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Image augmenting applications already on the market, such as Facetune and Perfect365, were limited to static images, whereas Looksery allowed augmented reality to live videos.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In late 2015 SnapChat purchased Looksery, which would then become its landmark lenses function.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Snapchat filter applications use face detection technology and on the basis of the facial features identified in an image a 3D mesh mask is layered over the face.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] A variety of technologies attempt to fool facial recognition software by the use of anti-facial recognition masks.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] DeepFace is a deep learning facial recognition system created by a research group at Facebook.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] It identifies human faces in digital images.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] It employs a nine-layer neural net with over 120 million connection weights, and was trained on four million images uploaded by Facebook users.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The system is said to be 97% accurate, compared to 85% for the FBI's Next Generation Identification system.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] TikTok's algorithm has been regarded as especially effective, but many were left to wonder at the exact programming that caused the app to be so effective in guessing the user's desired content.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In June 2020, TikTok released a statement regarding the "For You" page, and how they recommended videos to users, which did not include facial recognition.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In February 2021, however, TikTok agreed to a $92 million settlement to a US lawsuit which alleged that the app had used facial recognition in both user videos and its algorithm to identify age, gender and ethnicity.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The emerging use of facial recognition is in the use of ID verification services.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Many companies and others are working in the market now to provide these services to banks, ICOs, and other e-businesses.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2017, Apple's iPhone X smartphone introduced facial recognition to the product line with its "Face ID" platform, which uses an infrared illumination system.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Apple introduced Face ID on the flagship iPhone X as a biometric authentication successor to the Touch ID, a fingerprint based system.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Face ID has a facial recognition sensor that consists of two parts: a "Romeo" module that projects more than 30,000 infrared dots onto the user's face, and a "Juliet" module that reads the pattern.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The pattern is sent to a local "Secure Enclave" in the device's central processing unit (CPU) to confirm a match with the phone owner's face.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The facial pattern is not accessible by Apple.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The system will not work with eyes closed, in an effort to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The technology learns from changes in a user's appearance, and therefore works with hats, scarves, glasses, and many sunglasses, beard and makeup.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] This is done by using a "Flood Illuminator", which is a dedicated infrared flash that throws out invisible infrared light onto the user's face to get a 2d picture in addition to the 30,000 facial points.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Facial recognition algorithms can help in diagnosing some diseases using specific features on the nose, cheeks and other part of the human face.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Relying on developed data sets, machine learning has been used to identify genetic abnormalities just based on facial dimensions.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] FRT has also been used to verify patients before surgery procedures.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In March, 2022 according to a publication by Forbes, FDNA, an AI development company claimed that in the space of 10 years, they have worked with geneticists to develop a database of about 5,000 diseases and 1500 of them can be detected with facial recognition algorithms.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In an interview, the National Health Authority chief Dr.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Sharma said that facial recognition technology would be used in conjunction with Aadhaar to authenticate the identity of people seeking vaccines.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Ten human rights and digital rights organizations and more than 150 individuals signed a statement by the Internet Freedom Foundation that raised alarm against the deployment of facial recognition technology in the central government's vaccination drive process.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Implementation of an error-prone system without adequate legislation containing mandatory safeguards, would deprive citizens of essential services and linking this untested technology to the vaccination roll-out in India will only exclude persons from the vaccine delivery system.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In July, 2021, a press release by the Government of Meghalaya stated that facial recognition technology (FRT) would be used to verify the identity of pensioners to issue a Digital Life Certificate using "Pensioner's Life Certification Verification" mobile application.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The notice, according to the press release, purports to offer pensioners "a secure, easy and hassle-free interface for verifying their liveness to the Pension Disbursing Authorities from the comfort of their homes using smart phones".
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Australian Border Force and New Zealand Customs Service have set up an automated border processing system called SmartGate that uses face recognition, which compares the face of the traveller with the data in the e-passport microchip.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] All Canadian international airports use facial recognition as part of the Primary Inspection Kiosk program that compares a traveler face to their photo stored on the ePassport.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] This program first came to Vancouver International Airport in early 2017 and was rolled up to all remaining international airports in 2018–2019.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Police forces in the United Kingdom have been trialing live facial recognition technology at public events since 2015.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In May 2017, a man was arrested using an automatic facial recognition (AFR) system mounted on a van operated by the South Wales Police.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Ars Technica reported that "this appears to be the first time [AFR] has led to an arrest".
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] However, a 2018 report by Big Brother Watch found that these systems were up to 98% inaccurate.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The report also revealed that two UK police forces, South Wales Police and the Metropolitan Police, were using live facial recognition at public events and in public spaces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In September 2019, South Wales Police use of facial recognition was ruled lawful.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Live facial recognition has been trialled since 2016 in the streets of London and will be used on a regular basis from Metropolitan Police from beginning of 2020.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In August 2020 the Court of Appeal ruled that the way the facial recognition system had been used by the South Wales Police in 2017 and 2018 violated human rights.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] However, by 2024 the Metropolitan Police were using the technique with a database of 16,000 suspects, leading to over 360 arrests, including rapists and someone wanted for grievous bodily harm for 8 years.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] They claim a false positive rate of only 1 in 6,000.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The photos of those not identified by the system are deleted immediately.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Department of State operates one of the largest face recognition systems in the world with a database of 117 million American adults, with photos typically drawn from driver's license photos.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Although it is still far from completion, it is being put to use in certain cities to give clues as to who was in the photo.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The FBI uses the photos as an investigative tool, not for positive identification.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] As of 2016, facial recognition was being used to identify people in photos taken by police in San Diego and Los Angeles (not on real-time video, and only against booking photos) and use was planned in West Virginia and Dallas.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In recent years Maryland has used face recognition by comparing people's faces to their driver's license photos.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The system drew controversy when it was used in Baltimore to arrest unruly protesters after the death of Freddie Gray in police custody.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Many other states are using or developing a similar system however some states have laws prohibiting its use.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The FBI has also instituted its Next Generation Identification program to include face recognition, as well as more traditional biometrics like fingerprints and iris scans, which can pull from both criminal and civil databases.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The federal Government Accountability Office criticized the FBI for not addressing various concerns related to privacy and accuracy.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Customs and Border Protection deployed "biometric face scanners" at U.S. airports.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Passengers taking outbound international flights can complete the check-in, security and the boarding process after getting facial images captured and verified by matching their ID photos stored on CBP's database.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Images captured for travelers with U.S. citizenship will be deleted within up to 12-hours.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Transportation Security Administration (TSA) had expressed its intention to adopt a similar program for domestic air travel during the security check process in the future.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The American Civil Liberties Union is one of the organizations against the program, concerning that the program will be used for surveillance purposes.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2019, researchers reported that Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) uses facial recognition software against state driver's license databases, including for some states that provide licenses to undocumented immigrants.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In December 2022, 16 major domestic airports in the US started testing facial-recognition tech where kiosks with cameras are checking the photos on travelers' IDs to make sure that passengers are not impostors.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2006, the "Skynet" (天網) Project was initiated by the Chinese government to implement CCTV surveillance nationwide and as of 2018, there have been 20 million cameras, many of which are capable of real-time facial recognition, deployed across the country for this project.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Some official claim that the current Skynet system can scan the entire Chinese population in one second and the world population in two seconds.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2017, the Qingdao police was able to identify twenty-five wanted suspects using facial recognition equipment at the Qingdao International Beer Festival, one of which had been on the run for 10 years.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The equipment works by recording a 15-second video clip and taking multiple snapshots of the subject.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] That data is compared and analyzed with images from the police department's database and within 20 minutes, the subject can be identified with a 98.1% accuracy.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2018, Chinese police in Zhengzhou and Beijing were using smart glasses to take photos which are compared against a government database using facial recognition to identify suspects, retrieve an address, and track people moving beyond their home areas.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] As of late 2017, China has deployed facial recognition and artificial intelligence technology in Xinjiang.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Reporters visiting the region found surveillance cameras installed every hundred meters or so in several cities, as well as facial recognition checkpoints at areas like gas stations, shopping centers, and mosque entrances.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In May 2019, Human Rights Watch reported finding Face++ code in the Integrated Joint Operations Platform (IJOP), a police surveillance app used to collect data on, and track the Uighur community in Xinjiang.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Human Rights Watch released a correction to its report in June 2019 stating that the Chinese company Megvii did not appear to have collaborated on IJOP, and that the Face++ code in the app was inoperable.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In February 2020, following the Coronavirus outbreak, Megvii applied for a bank loan to optimize the body temperature screening system it had launched to help identify people with symptoms of a Coronavirus infection in crowds.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In its loan application documents, Megvii stated that it needed to improve the accuracy of identifying masked individuals.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Many public places in China are implemented with facial recognition equipment, including railway stations, airports, tourist attractions, expos, and office buildings.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In October 2019, a professor at Zhejiang Sci-Tech University sued the Hangzhou Safari Park for abusing private biometric information of customers.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The safari park uses facial recognition technology to verify the identities of its Year Card holders.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] An estimated 300 tourist sites in China have installed facial recognition systems and use them to admit visitors.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] This case is reported to be the first on the use of facial recognition systems in China.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In August 2020, Radio Free Asia reported that in 2019 Geng Guanjun, a citizen of Taiyuan City who had used the WeChat app by Tencent to forward a video to a friend in the United States was subsequently convicted on the charge of the crime "picking quarrels and provoking troubles".
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Court documents showed that the Chinese police used a facial recognition system to identify Geng Guanjun as an "overseas democracy activist" and that China's network management and propaganda departments directly monitor WeChat users.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2019, Protestors in Hong Kong destroyed smart lampposts amid concerns they could contain cameras and facial recognition system used for surveillance by Chinese authorities.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Human rights groups have criticized the Chinese government for using artificial intelligence facial recognition technology in its suppression against Uyghurs, Christians and Falun Gong practitioners.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Even though facial recognition technology (FRT) is not fully accurate, it is being increasingly deployed for identification purposes by the police in India.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] FRT systems generate a probability match score, or a confidence score between the suspect who is to be identified and the database of identified criminals that is available with the police.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The National Automated Facial Recognition System (AFRS) is already being developed by the National Crime Records Bureau (NCRB), a body constituted under the Ministry of Home Affairs.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The project seeks to develop and deploy a national database of photographs which would comport with a facial recognition technology system by the central and state security agencies.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Internet Freedom Foundation has flagged concerns regarding the project.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The NGO has highlighted that the accuracy of FRT systems are "routinely exaggerated and the real numbers leave much to be desired.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Under the Supreme Court of India's decision in *Justice K.S.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Crime and Criminal Tracking Network and Systems (CCTNS), which is a Mission Mode Project under the National e-Governance Plan (NeGP), is viewed as a system which would connect police stations across India, and help them "talk" to each other.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The project's objective is to digitize all FIR-related information, including FIRs registered, as well as cases investigated, charge sheets filed, and suspects and wanted persons in all police stations.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] This shall constitute a national database of crime and criminals in India.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] CCTNS is being implemented without a data protection law in place.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] CCTNS is proposed to be integrated with the AFRS, a repository of all crime and criminal related facial data which can be deployed to purportedly identify or verify a person from a variety of inputs ranging from images to videos.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] This has raised privacy concerns from civil society organizations and privacy experts.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Both the projects have been censured as instruments of "mass surveillance" at the hands of the state.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In Rajasthan, 'RajCop,' a police app has been recently integrated with a facial recognition module which can match the face of a suspect against a database of known persons in real-time.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The state of Telangana has installed 8 lakh CCTV cameras, with its capital city Hyderabad slowly turning into a surveillance capital.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] A false positive happens when facial recognition technology misidentifies a person to be someone they are not, that is, it yields an incorrect positive result.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] They often results in discrimination and strengthening of existing biases.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] For example, in 2018, Delhi Police reported that its FRT system had an accuracy rate of 2%, which sank to 1% in 2019.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The FRT system even failed to distinguish accurately between different sexes.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The government of Delhi in collaboration with Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) is developing a new technology called Crime Mapping Analytics and Predictive System (CMAPS).
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The project aims to deploy space technology for "controlling crime and maintaining law and order." The system will be connected to a database containing data of criminals.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The technology is envisaged to be deployed to collect real-time data at the crime scene.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] A Right to Information (RTI) request dated July 30, 2020 was filed with the Office of the Commissioner, Kolkata Police, seeking information about the facial recognition technology that the department was using.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The information sought was denied stating that the department was exempted from disclosure under section 24(4) of the RTI Act.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In the 2000 Mexican presidential election, the Mexican government employed face recognition software to prevent voter fraud.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Some individuals had been registering to vote under several different names, in an attempt to place multiple votes.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] By comparing new face images to those already in the voter database, authorities were able to reduce duplicate registrations.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In Colombia public transport busses are fitted with a facial recognition system by FaceFirst Inc to identify passengers that are sought by the National Police of Colombia.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] FaceFirst Inc also built the facial recognition system for Tocumen International Airport in Panama.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The face recognition system is deployed to identify individuals among the travellers that are sought by the Panamanian National Police or Interpol.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Tocumen International Airport operates an airport-wide surveillance system using hundreds of live face recognition cameras to identify wanted individuals passing through the airport.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] At the 2014 FIFA World Cup in Brazil the Federal Police of Brazil used face recognition goggles.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Face recognition systems "made in China" were also deployed at the 2016 Summer Olympics in Rio de Janeiro.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Nuctech Company provided 145 inspection terminals for Maracanã Stadium and 55 terminals for the Deodoro Olympic Park.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Police forces in at least 21 countries of the European Union use, or plan to use, facial recognition systems, either for administrative or criminal purposes.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Greek police passed a contract with Intracom-Telecom for the provision of at least 1,000 devices equipped with live facial recognition system.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The delivery is expected before the summer 2021.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The total value of the contract is over 4 million euros, paid for in large part by the Internal Security Fund of the European Commission.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Italian police acquired a face recognition system in 2017, Sistema Automatico Riconoscimento Immagini (SARI).
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In November 2020, the Interior ministry announced plans to use it in real-time to identify people suspected of seeking asylum.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Netherlands has deployed facial recognition and artificial intelligence technology since 2016.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The database of the Dutch police currently contains over 2.2 million pictures of 1.3 million Dutch citizens.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] This accounts for about 8% of the population.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In The Netherlands, face recognition is not used by the police on municipal CCTV.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In South Africa, in 2016, the city of Johannesburg announced it was rolling out smart CCTV cameras complete with automatic number plate recognition and facial recognition.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The US firm 3VR, now Identiv, is an example of a vendor which began offering facial recognition systems and services to retailers as early as 2007.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2018, the National Retail Federation Loss Prevention Research Council called facial recognition technology "a promising new tool" worth evaluating.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In July 2020, the Reuters news agency reported that during the 2010s the pharmacy chain Rite Aid had deployed facial recognition video surveillance systems and components from FaceFirst, DeepCam LLC, and other vendors at some retail locations in the United States.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In a 2020 statement to Reuters in response to the reporting, Rite Aid said that it had ceased using the facial recognition software and switched off the cameras.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] According to director Read Hayes of the National Retail Federation Loss Prevention Research Council, Rite Aid's surveillance program was either the largest or one of the largest programs in retail.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Home Depot, Menards, Walmart, and 7-Eleven are among other US retailers also engaged in large-scale pilot programs or deployments of facial recognition technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Rite Aid said that the selection of locations was "data-driven", based on the theft histories of individual stores, local and national crime data, and site infrastructure.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2019, facial recognition to prevent theft was in use at Sydney's Star Casino and was also deployed at gaming venues in New Zealand.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In June 2022, consumer group CHOICE reported facial recognition was in use in Australia at Kmart, Bunnings, and The Good Guys.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The Good Guys subsequently suspended the technology pending a legal challenge by CHOICE to the Office of the Australian Information Commissioner, while Bunnings kept the technology in use and Kmart maintained its trial of the technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] At the American football championship game Super Bowl XXXV in January 2001, police in Tampa Bay, Florida used Viisage face recognition software to search for potential criminals and terrorists in attendance at the event.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] 19 people with minor criminal records were potentially identified.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Face recognition systems have also been used by photo management software to identify the subjects of photographs, enabling features such as searching images by person, as well as suggesting photos to be shared with a specific contact if their presence were detected in a photo.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] By 2008 facial recognition systems were typically used as access control in security systems.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The United States' popular music and country music celebrity Taylor Swift surreptitiously employed facial recognition technology at a concert in 2018.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The camera was embedded in a kiosk near a ticket booth and scanned concert-goers as they entered the facility for known stalkers.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] On August 18, 2019, *The Times* reported that the UAE-owned Manchester City hired a Texas-based firm, Blink Identity, to deploy facial recognition systems in a driver program.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The club has planned a single super-fast lane for the supporters at the Etihad stadium.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] However, civil rights groups cautioned the club against the introduction of this technology, saying that it would risk "normalising a mass surveillance tool".
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The policy and campaigns officer at Liberty, Hannah Couchman said that Man City's move is alarming, since the fans will be obliged to share deeply sensitive personal information with a private company, where they could be tracked and monitored in their everyday lives.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In 2019, casinos in Australia and New Zealand rolled out facial recognition to prevent theft, and a representative of Sydney's Star Casino said they would also provide 'customer service' like welcoming a patron back to a bar.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] In August 2020, amid the COVID-19 pandemic in the United States, American football stadiums of New York and Los Angeles announced the installation of facial recognition for upcoming matches.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] The purpose is to make the entry process as touchless as possible.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p01] Media companies have begun using face recognition technology to streamline their tracking, organizing, and archiving pictures and videos.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2006, the performance of the latest face recognition algorithms was evaluated in the Face Recognition Grand Challenge (FRGC).
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] High-resolution face images, 3-D face scans, and iris images were used in the tests.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The results indicated that the new algorithms are 10 times more accurate than the face recognition algorithms of 2002 and 100 times more accurate than those of 1995.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Some of the algorithms were able to outperform human participants in recognizing faces and could uniquely identify identical twins.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] One key advantage of a facial recognition system that it is able to perform mass identification as it does not require the cooperation of the test subject to work.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Properly designed systems installed in airports, multiplexes, and other public places can identify individuals among the crowd, without passers-by even being aware of the system.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, as compared to other biometric techniques, face recognition may not be most reliable and efficient.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Quality measures are very important in facial recognition systems as large degrees of variations are possible in face images.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Factors such as illumination, expression, pose and noise during face capture can affect the performance of facial recognition systems.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Among all biometric systems, facial recognition has the highest false acceptance and rejection rates, thus questions have been raised on the effectiveness of or bias of face recognition software in cases of railway and airport security, law enforcement and housing and employment decisions.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] This is one of the main obstacles of face recognition in surveillance systems.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] It has also been suggested that camera settings can favour sharper imagery of white skin than of other skin tones.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Face recognition is less effective if facial expressions vary.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] A big smile can render the system less effective.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] For instance: Canada, in 2009, allowed only neutral facial expressions in passport photos.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] There is also inconstancy in the datasets used by researchers.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Researchers may use anywhere from several subjects to scores of subjects and a few hundred images to thousands of images.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Data sets may be diverse and inclusive or mainly contain images of white males.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] It is important for researchers to make available the datasets they used to each other, or have at least a standard or representative dataset.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Although high degrees of accuracy have been claimed for some facial recognition systems, these outcomes are not universal.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The consistently worst accuracy rate is for those who are 18 to 30 years old, Black and female.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Studies have shown that facial recognition algorithms tend to perform better on individuals with lighter skin tones compared to those with darker skin tones.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] For example, a 2018 study found that leading commercial gender classification models, which are facial recognition models, have an error rate up to 7 times higher for those with darker skin tones compared to those with lighter skin tones.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Initially this disparity was attributed to the imbalance in training datasets, which often overrepresent lighter-skinned individuals, leading to higher error rates for darker-skinned people.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, later studies showed that dataset imbalance is not the sole cause for difference in performance.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Common image compression methods, such as JPEG chroma subsampling, have been found to disproportionately degrade performance for darker-skinned individuals.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] These methods inadequately represent color information, which adversely affects the ability of algorithms to recognize darker-skinned individuals accurately.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facial recognition systems often demonstrate lower accuracy when identifying individuals with non-Eurocentric facial features.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Known as the Cross-race effect, this bias occurs when systems perform better on racial or ethnic groups that are overrepresented in their training data, resulting in reduced accuracy for underrepresented groups.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The overrepresented group is generally the more populous group in the location that the model is being developed.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] For example, models developed in Asian cultures generally perform better on Asian facial features than Eurocentric facial features due to overrepresentation in the developers training dataset.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The opposite is observed in models developed in Eurocentric cultures.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The systems used for facial recognition often lack the sufficient training needed to fully recognize those features not of Eurocentric descent.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] When the training and databases for these Machine Learning (ML) models do not contain a diverse representation, the models fail to identify the missed population, adding to their racial biases.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The cross-race effect is not exclusive to machines; humans also experience difficulty recognizing faces from racial or ethnic groups different from their own.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] This is an example of inherent human biases being perpetuated in training datasets.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facial recognition technologies encounter significant challenges when identifying individuals with disabilities.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] For instance, systems have been shown to perform worse when recognizing individuals with Down syndrome, often leading to increased false match rates.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] This is due to distinct facial structures associated with the condition that are not adequately represented in training datasets.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] More broadly, facial recognition systems tend to overlook diverse physical characteristics related to disabilities.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The lack of representative data for individuals with varying disabilities further emphasizes the need for inclusive algorithmic designs to mitigate bias and improve accuracy.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Additionally, facial expression recognition technologies often fail to accurately interpret the emotional states of individuals with intellectual disabilities.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] This shortcoming can hinder effective communication and interaction, underscoring the necessity for systems trained on diverse datasets that include individuals with intellectual disabilities.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Furthermore, biases in facial recognition algorithms can lead to discriminatory outcomes for people with disabilities.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] For example, certain facial features or asymmetries may result in misidentification or exclusion, highlighting the importance of developing accessible and fair biometric systems.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] A review in 2025 showed improved mitigation of demographic biases in face recognition: by processing at input, model, or output stages.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Additionally, targeted dataset collection has been shown to improve racial equity in facial recognition systems.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] By prioritizing diverse data inputs, researchers demonstrated measurable reductions in performance disparities between racial groups.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Critics of the technology complain that the London Borough of Newham scheme has, as of 2004, never recognized a single criminal, despite several criminals in the system's database living in the Borough and the system has been running for several years.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] "Not once, as far as the police know, has Newham's automatic face recognition system spotted a live target." This information seems to conflict with claims that the system was credited with a 34% reduction in crime (hence why it was rolled out to Birmingham also).
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] An experiment in 2002 by the local police department in Tampa, Florida, had similarly disappointing results.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] A system at Boston's Logan Airport was shut down in 2003 after failing to make any matches during a two-year test period.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2014, Facebook stated that in a standardized two-option facial recognition test, its online system scored 97.25% accuracy, compared to the human benchmark of 97.5%.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Systems are often advertised as having accuracy near 100%; this is misleading as the outcomes are not universal.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The studies often use samples that are smaller and less diverse than would be necessary for large scale applications.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Because facial recognition is not completely accurate, it creates a list of potential matches.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] A human operator must then look through these potential matches and studies show the operators pick the correct match out of the list only about half the time.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] This causes the issue of targeting the wrong suspect.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Civil rights organizations and privacy campaigners such as the Electronic Frontier Foundation, Big Brother Watch and the ACLU express concern that privacy is being compromised by the use of surveillance technologies.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Face recognition can be used not just to identify an individual, but also to unearth other personal data associated with an individual – such as other photos featuring the individual, blog posts, social media profiles, Internet behavior, and travel patterns.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Concerns have been raised over who would have access to the knowledge of one's whereabouts and people with them at any given time.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Moreover, individuals have limited ability to avoid or thwart face recognition tracking unless they hide their faces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] This fundamentally changes the dynamic of day-to-day privacy by enabling any marketer, government agency, or random stranger to secretly collect the identities and associated personal information of any individual captured by the face recognition system.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Consumers may not understand or be aware of what their data is being used for, which denies them the ability to consent to how their personal information gets shared.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In July 2015, the United States Government Accountability Office conducted a Report to the Ranking Member, Subcommittee on Privacy, Technology and the Law, Committee on the Judiciary, U.S.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The report discussed facial recognition technology's commercial uses, privacy issues, and the applicable federal law.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] It states that previously, issues concerning facial recognition technology were discussed and represent the need for updating the privacy laws of the United States so that federal law continually matches the impact of advanced technologies.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The report noted that some industry, government, and private organizations were in the process of developing, or have developed, "voluntary privacy guidelines".
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] These guidelines varied between the stakeholders, but their overall aim was to gain consent and inform citizens of the intended use of facial recognition technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] According to the report the voluntary privacy guidelines helped to counteract the privacy concerns that arise when citizens are unaware of how their personal data gets put to use.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In December 2017, Facebook rolled out a new feature that notifies a user when someone uploads a photo that includes what Facebook thinks is their face, even if they are not tagged.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facebook has attempted to frame the new functionality in a positive light, amidst prior backlashes.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facebook's head of privacy, Rob Sherman, addressed this new feature as one that gives people more control over their photos online.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] "We've thought about this as a really empowering feature," he says.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The most recent case was dismissed in January 2016 because the court lacked jurisdiction.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the US, surveillance companies such as Clearview AI are relying on the First Amendment to the United States Constitution to data scrape user accounts on social media platforms for data that can be used in the development of facial recognition systems.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2019, the *Financial Times* first reported that facial recognition software was in use in the King's Cross area of London.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The development around London's King's Cross mainline station includes shops, offices, Google's UK HQ and part of St Martin's College.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In September 2019 it was announced by Argent that facial recognition software would no longer be used at King's Cross.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Argent claimed that the software had been deployed between May 2016 and March 2018 on two cameras covering a pedestrian street running through the centre of the development.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In October 2019, a report by the deputy London mayor Sophie Linden revealed that in a secret deal the Metropolitan Police had passed photos of seven people to Argent for use in their King's cross facial recognition system.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Automated Facial Recognition was trialled by the South Wales Police on multiple occasions between 2017 and 2019.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The use of the technology was challenged in court by a private individual, Edward Bridges, with support from the charity Liberty (case known as R (Bridges) v Chief Constable South Wales Police).
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The case was heard in the Court of Appeal and a judgement was given in August 2020.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The case argued that the use of Facial Recognition was a privacy violation on the basis that there was insufficient legal framework or proportionality in the use of Facial Recognition and that its use was in violation of the Data Protection Acts 1998 and 2018.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The case was decided in favour of Bridges and did not award damages.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The case was settled via a declaration of wrongdoing.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In response to the case, the British Government has repeatedly attempted to pass a Bill regulating the use of Facial Recognition in public spaces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The proposed Bills have attempted to appoint a Commissioner with the ability to regulate Facial Recognition use by Government Services in a similar manner to the Commissioner for CCTV.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Such a Bill has yet to come into force [correct as of September 2021].
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] She noted such a move would could go against federal, state, and local human rights laws.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] As of 2018, it is still contested as to whether or not facial recognition technology works less accurately on people of color.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] One study by Joy Buolamwini (MIT Media Lab) and Timnit Gebru (Microsoft Research) found that the error rate for gender recognition for women of color within three commercial facial recognition systems ranged from 23.8% to 36%, whereas for lighter-skinned men it was between 0.0 and 1.6%.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Overall accuracy rates for identifying men (91.9%) were higher than for women (79.4%), and none of the systems accommodated a non-binary understanding of gender.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] It also showed that the datasets used to train commercial facial recognition models were unrepresentative of the broader population and skewed toward lighter-skinned males.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, another study showed that several commercial facial recognition software sold to law enforcement offices around the country had a lower false non-match rate for black people than for white people.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Experts fear that face recognition systems may actually be hurting citizens the police claims they are trying to protect.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The lack of regulations holding facial recognition technology companies to requirements of racially biased testing can be a significant flaw in the adoption of use in law enforcement.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] CyberExtruder, a company that markets itself to law enforcement said that they had not performed testing or research on bias in their software.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] CyberExtruder did note that some skin colors are more difficult for the software to recognize with current limitations of the technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] "Just as individuals with very dark skin are hard to identify with high significance via facial recognition, individuals with very pale skin are the same," said Blake Senftner, a senior software engineer at CyberExtruder.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The United States' National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) carried out extensive testing of FRT system 1:1 verification and 1:many identification.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] It also tested for the differing accuracy of FRT across different demographic groups.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The independent study concluded at present, no FRT system has 100% accuracy.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2010, Peru passed the Law for Personal Data Protection, which defines biometric information that can be used to identify an individual as sensitive data.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2012, Colombia passed a comprehensive Data Protection Law which defines biometric data as sensitive information.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] According to Article 9(1) of the EU's 2016 General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) the processing of biometric data for the purpose of "uniquely identifying a natural person" is sensitive and the facial recognition data processed in this way becomes sensitive personal data.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In September 2019 the Swedish Data Protection Authority (DPA) issued its first ever financial penalty for a violation of the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) against a school that was using the technology to replace time-consuming roll calls during class.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The DPA found that the school illegally obtained the biometric data of its students without completing an impact assessment.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In addition the school did not make the DPA aware of the pilot scheme.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the United States of America several U.S. states have passed laws to protect the privacy of biometric data.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Examples include the Illinois Biometric Information Privacy Act (BIPA) and the California Consumer Privacy Act (CCPA).
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In March 2020 California residents filed a class action against Clearview AI, alleging that the company had illegally collected biometric data online and with the help of face recognition technology built up a database of biometric data which was sold to companies and police forces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] At the time Clearview AI already faced two lawsuits under BIPA and an investigation by the Privacy Commissioner of Canada for compliance with the Personal Information Protection and Electronic Documents Act (PIPEDA).
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In May 2019, San Francisco, California became the first major United States city to ban the use of facial recognition software for police and other local government agencies' usage.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] San Francisco Supervisor, Aaron Peskin, introduced regulations that will require agencies to gain approval from the San Francisco Board of Supervisors to purchase surveillance technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The regulations also require that agencies publicly disclose the intended use for new surveillance technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In June 2019, Somerville, Massachusetts became the first city on the East Coast to ban face surveillance software for government use, specifically in police investigations and municipal surveillance.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In July 2019, Oakland, California banned the usage of facial recognition technology by city departments.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The American Civil Liberties Union ("ACLU") has campaigned across the United States for transparency in surveillance technology and has supported both San Francisco and Somerville's ban on facial recognition software.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The ACLU works to challenge the secrecy and surveillance with this technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] During the George Floyd protests, use of facial recognition by city government was banned in Boston, Massachusetts.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The West Lafayette, Indiana City Council passed an ordinance banning facial recognition surveillance technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] On October 27, 2020, 22 human rights groups called upon the University of Miami to ban facial recognition technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] This came after the students accused the school of using the software to identify student protesters.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The allegations were, however, denied by the university.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] A state police reform law in Massachusetts will take effect in July 2021; a ban passed by the legislature was rejected by governor Charlie Baker.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Instead, the law requires a judicial warrant, limit the personnel who can perform the search, record data about how the technology is used, and create a commission to make recommendations about future regulations.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Reports in 2024 revealed that some police departments, including San Francisco Police Department, had skirted bans on facial recognition technology that had been enacted in their respective cities.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In January 2020, the European Union suggested, but then quickly scrapped, a proposed moratorium on facial recognition in public spaces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The European "Reclaim Your Face" coalition launched in October 2020.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The coalition calls for a ban on facial recognition and launched a European Citizens' Initiative in February 2021.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] More than 60 organizations call on the European Commission to strictly regulate the use of biometric surveillance technologies.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the 18th and 19th century, the belief that facial expressions revealed the moral worth or true inner state of a human was widespread and physiognomy was a respected science in the Western world.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] From the early 19th century onwards photography was used in the physiognomic analysis of facial features and facial expression to detect insanity and dementia.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the 1960s and 1970s the study of human emotions and its expressions was reinvented by psychologists, who tried to define a normal range of emotional responses to events.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The research on automated emotion recognition has since the 1970s focused on facial expressions and speech, which are regarded as the two most important ways in which humans communicate emotions to other humans.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the 1970s the Facial Action Coding System (FACS) categorization for the physical expression of emotions was established.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Its developer Paul Ekman maintains that there are six emotions that are universal to all human beings and that these can be coded in facial expressions.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Research into automatic emotion specific expression recognition has in the past decades focused on frontal view images of human faces.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facial thermography can be considered as a promising tool of emotion recognition.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2016, facial feature emotion recognition algorithms were among the new technologies, alongside high-definition CCTV, high resolution 3D face recognition and iris recognition, that found their way out of university research labs.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In 2016, Facebook acquired FacioMetrics, a facial feature emotion recognition corporate spin-off by Carnegie Mellon University.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In the same year Apple Inc. acquired the facial feature emotion recognition start-up Emotient.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] By the end of 2016, commercial vendors of facial recognition systems offered to integrate and deploy emotion recognition algorithms for facial features.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The MIT's Media Lab spin-off Affectiva by late 2019 offered a facial expression emotion detection product that can recognize emotions in humans while driving.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The development of anti-facial recognition technology is effectively an arms race between privacy researchers and big data companies.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Big data companies increasingly use convolutional AI technology to create ever more advanced facial recognition models.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Solutions to block facial recognition may not work on newer software, or on different types of facial recognition models.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] One popular cited example of facial-recognition blocking is the CVDazzle makeup and haircut system, but the creators note on their website that it has been outdated for quite some time as it was designed to combat a particular facial recognition algorithm and may not work.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Another example is the emergence of facial recognition that can identify people wearing facemasks and sunglasses, especially after the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Given that big data companies have much more funding than privacy researchers, it is very difficult for anti-facial recognition systems to keep up.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] There is also no guarantee that obfuscation techniques that were used for images taken in the past and stored, such as masks or software obfuscation, would protect users from facial-recognition analysis of those images by future technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] In January 2013, Japanese researchers from the National Institute of Informatics created 'privacy visor' glasses that use nearly infrared light to make the face underneath it unrecognizable to face recognition software that use infrared.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The latest version uses a titanium frame, light-reflective material and a mask which uses angles and patterns to disrupt facial recognition technology through both absorbing and bouncing back light sources.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, these methods are used to prevent infrared facial recognition and would not work on AI facial recognition of plain images.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Some projects use adversarial machine learning to come up with new printed patterns that confuse existing face recognition software.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] One method that may work to protect from facial recognition systems are specific haircuts and make-up patterns that prevent the used algorithms to detect a face, known as computer vision dazzle.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Incidentally, the makeup styles popular with Juggalos may also protect against facial recognition.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Facial masks that are worn to protect from contagious viruses can reduce the accuracy of facial recognition systems.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] A 2020 NIST study, tested popular one-to-one matching systems and found a failure rate between five and fifty percent on masked individuals.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] *The Verge* speculated that the accuracy rate of mass surveillance systems, which were not included in the study, would be even less accurate than the accuracy of one-to-one matching systems.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] The facial recognition of Apple Pay can work through many barriers, including heavy makeup, thick beards and even sunglasses, but fails with masks.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, facial recognition of masked faces is increasingly getting more reliable.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Another solution is the application of obfuscation to images that may fool facial recognition systems while still appearing normal to a human user.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] These could be used for when images are posted online or on social media.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, as it is hard to remove images once they are on the internet, the obfuscation on these images may be defeated and the face of the user identified by future advances in technology.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] Two examples of this technique, developed in 2020, are the ANU's 'Camera Adversaria' camera app, and the University of Chicago's Fawkes image cloaking software algorithm which applies obfuscation to already taken photos.
[src:mediapipe/facial-recognition-system-p02] However, by 2021 the Fawkes obfuscation algorithm had already been specifically targeted by Microsoft Azure which changed its algorithm to lower Fawkes' effectiveness.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Gesture recognition offers a path for computers to begin to better understand and interpret human body language, previously not possible through text or unenhanced graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Gestures can originate from any bodily motion or state, but commonly originate from the face or hand.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] One area of the field is emotion recognition derived from facial expressions and hand gestures.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Users can make simple gestures to control or interact with devices without physically touching them.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Many approaches have been made using cameras and computer vision algorithms to interpret sign language, however, the identification and recognition of posture, gait, proxemics, and human behaviors is also the subject of gesture recognition techniques.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Gesture recognition can be conducted with techniques from computer vision and image processing.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The literature includes ongoing work in the computer vision field on capturing gestures or more general human pose and movements by cameras connected to a computer.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The term "gesture recognition" has been used to refer more narrowly to non-text-input handwriting symbols, such as inking on a graphics tablet, multi-touch gestures, and mouse gesture recognition.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] This is computer interaction through the drawing of symbols with a pointing device cursor.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Pen computing expands digital gesture recognition beyond traditional input devices such as keyboards and mice, and reduces the hardware impact of a system.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] A touchless user interface (TUI) is an emerging type of technology wherein a device is controlled via body motion and gestures without touching a keyboard, mouse, or screen.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] There are several devices utilizing this type of interface such as smartphones, laptops, games, TVs, and music equipment.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] One type of touchless interface uses the Bluetooth connectivity of a smartphone to activate a company's visitor management system.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] This eliminates having to touch an interface, for convenience or to avoid a potential source of contamination as during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The ability to track a person's movements and determine what gestures they may be performing can be achieved through various tools.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Kinetic user interfaces (KUIs) are an emerging type of user interfaces that allow users to interact with computing devices through the motion of objects and bodies.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Examples of KUIs include tangible user interfaces and motion-aware games such as Wii and Microsoft's Kinect, and other interactive projects.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Although there is a large amount of research done in image/video-based gesture recognition, there is some variation in the tools and environments used between implementations.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Depending on the type of input data, the approach for interpreting a gesture could be done in different ways.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] However, most of the techniques rely on key pointers represented in a 3D coordinate system.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Based on the relative motion of these, the gesture can be detected with high accuracy, depending on the quality of the input and the algorithm's approach.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] In order to interpret movements of the body, one has to classify them according to common properties and the message the movements may express.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] For example, in sign language, each gesture represents a word or phrase.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Some literature differentiates 2 different approaches in gesture recognition: a 3D model-based and an appearance-based.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The foremost method makes use of 3D information on key elements of the body parts in order to obtain several important parameters, like palm position or joint angles.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Approaches derived from it such as the volumetric models have proven to be very intensive in terms of computational power and require further technological developments in order to be implemented for real-time analysis.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Alternately, appearance-based systems use images or videos for direct interpretation.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Such models are easier to process, but usually lack the generality required for human-computer interaction.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The 3D model approach can use volumetric or skeletal models or even a combination of the two.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Volumetric approaches have been heavily used in the computer animation industry and for computer vision purposes.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The models are generally created from complicated 3D surfaces, like NURBS or polygon meshes.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The drawback of this method is that it is very computationally intensive, and systems for real-time analysis are still to be developed.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] For the moment, a more interesting approach would be to map simple primitive objects to the person's most important body parts (for example cylinders for the arms and neck, sphere for the head) and analyze the way these interact with each other.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Furthermore, some abstract structures like super-quadrics and generalized cylinders maybe even more suitable for approximating the body parts.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Instead of using intensive processing of the 3D models and dealing with a lot of parameters, one can just use a simplified version of joint angle parameters along with segment lengths.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] This is known as a skeletal representation of the body, where a virtual skeleton of the person is computed and parts of the body are mapped to certain segments.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Appearance-based models no longer use a spatial representation of the body, instead deriving their parameters directly from the images or videos using a template database.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Some are based on the deformable 2D templates of the human parts of the body, particularly the hands.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Deformable templates are sets of points on the outline of an object, used as interpolation nodes for the object's outline approximation.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] One of the simplest interpolation functions is linear, which performs an average shape from point sets, point variability parameters, and external deformation.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] These template-based models are mostly used for hand-tracking, but could also be used for simple gesture classification.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The second approach in gesture detection using appearance-based models uses image sequences as gesture templates.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Parameters for this method are either the images themselves, or certain features derived from these.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Most of the time, only one (monoscopic) or two (stereoscopic) views are used.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Electromyography (EMG) concerns the study of electrical signals produced by muscles in the body.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Through classification of data received from the arm muscles, it is possible to classify the action and thus input the gesture to external software.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Consumer EMG devices allow for non-invasive approaches such as an arm or leg band and connect via Bluetooth.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Due to this, EMG has an advantage over visual methods since the user does not need to face a camera to give input, enabling more freedom of movement.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] There are many challenges associated with the accuracy and usefulness of gesture recognition and software designed to implement it.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] For image-based gesture recognition, there are limitations on the equipment used and image noise.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Images or video may not be under consistent lighting, or in the same location.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Items in the background or distinct features of the users may make recognition more difficult.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The variety of implementations for image-based gesture recognition may also cause issues with the viability of the technology for general usage.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] For example, an algorithm calibrated for one camera may not work for a different camera.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The amount of background noise also causes tracking and recognition difficulties, especially when occlusions (partial and full) occur.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Furthermore, the distance from the camera, and the camera's resolution and quality, also cause variations in recognition accuracy.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] In order to capture human gestures by visual sensors robust computer vision methods are also required, for example for hand tracking and hand posture recognition or for capturing movements of the head, facial expressions or gaze direction.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] One significant challenge to the adoption of gesture interfaces on consumer mobile devices such as smartphones and smartwatches stems from the social acceptability implications of gestural input.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] While gestures can facilitate fast and accurate input on many novel form-factor computers, their adoption and usefulness are often limited by social factors rather than technical ones.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] To this end, designers of gesture input methods may seek to balance both technical considerations and user willingness to perform gestures in different social contexts.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] In addition, different device hardware and sensing mechanisms support different kinds of recognizable gestures.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Gesture interfaces on mobile and small form-factor devices are often supported by the presence of motion sensors such as inertial measurement units (IMUs).
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] On these devices, gesture sensing relies on users performing movement-based gestures capable of being recognized by these motion sensors.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] This can potentially make capturing signals from subtle or low-motion gestures challenging, as they may become difficult to distinguish from natural movements or noise.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] The social acceptability of mobile device gestures relies heavily on the naturalness of the gesture and social context.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Wearable computers typically differ from traditional mobile devices in that their usage and interaction location takes place on the user's body.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] In these contexts, gesture interfaces may become preferred over traditional input methods, as their small size renders touch-screens or keyboards less appealing.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Nevertheless, they share many of the same social acceptability obstacles as mobile devices when it comes to gestural interaction.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] However, the possibility of wearable computers being hidden from sight or integrated into other everyday objects, such as clothing, allow gesture input to mimic common clothing interactions, such as adjusting a shirt collar or rubbing one's front pant pocket.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] A major consideration for wearable computer interaction is the location for device placement and interaction.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] A study exploring third-party attitudes towards wearable device interaction conducted across the United States and South Korea found differences in the perception of wearable computing use of males and females, in part due to different areas of the body considered socially sensitive.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Another study investigating the social acceptability of on-body projected interfaces found similar results, with both studies labelling areas around the waist, groin, and upper body (for women) to be least acceptable while areas around the forearm and wrist to be most acceptable.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Public Installations, such as interactive public displays, allow access to information and displays interactive media in public settings such as museums, galleries, and theaters.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] While touch screens are a frequent form of input for public displays, gesture interfaces provide additional benefits such as improved hygiene, interaction from a distance, and improved discoverability, and may favor performative interaction.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] An important consideration for gestural interaction with public displays is the high probability or expectation of a spectator audience.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] Arm fatigue was a side-effect of vertically oriented touch-screen or light-pen use.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] In periods of prolonged use, users' arms began to feel fatigued and/or discomfort.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] This effect contributed to the decline of touch-screen input despite its initial popularity in the 1980s.
[src:mediapipe/gesture-recognition] In order to measure arm fatigue side effect, researchers developed a technique called Consumed Endurance.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] The concept of optic flow has roots as far back as Euclid's *Optics*, but its modern formulation arose from Second World War research into pilot vision during landing.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Several researchers arrived at the idea independently; James J.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Gibson gave it its most influential treatment, publishing his theory in 1947 and created the term "optic flow" in 1950.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Optical flow can be estimated in a number of ways.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Many classical models use the intuitive assumption of *brightness constancy*; that even if a point moves between frames, its brightness stays constant.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] To formalise this intuitive assumption, consider two consecutive frames from a video sequence, with intensity $I(x,y,t)$ , where $(x,y)$ refer to pixel coordinates and t refers to time.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] where $\mathbf {w$ is the displacement vector between a point in the first frame and the corresponding point in the second frame.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] By itself, the brightness constancy constraint cannot be solved for u and v at each pixel, since there is only one equation and two unknowns.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] This is known as the *aperture problem*.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Therefore, additional constraints must be imposed to estimate the flow field.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Perhaps the most natural approach to addressing the aperture problem is to apply a smoothness constraint or a *regularization constraint* to the flow field.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] where $\Omega$ is the extent of the images $I(x,y)$ , $\nabla$ is the gradient operator, $\alpha$ is a constant, and $\Psi ()$ is a loss function.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] This optimisation problem is difficult to solve owing to its non-linearity.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] To address this issue, one can use a *variational approach* and linearise the brightness constancy constraint using a first order Taylor series approximation.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] For convenience, the derivatives of the image, ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial x}}$ , ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial y}}$ and ${\tfrac {\partial I}{\partial t}}$ are often condensed to become $I_{x}$ , $I_{y}$ and $I_{t}$ .
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] For the choice of $\Psi (x)=x^{2}$ , this method is the same as the Horn-Schunck method.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Of course, other choices of cost function have been used such as $\Psi (x)={\sqrt {x^{2}+\epsilon ^{2}}}$ , which is a differentiable variant of the $L^{1}$ norm.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] To solve the aforementioned optimization problem, one can use the Euler-Lagrange equations to provide a system of partial differential equations for each point in $I(x,y,t)$ .
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Since the image data is made up of discrete pixels, these equations are discretised.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Doing so yields a system of linear equations which can be solved for $(u,v)$ at each pixel, using an iterative scheme such as Gauss-Seidel.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Although, linearising the brightness constancy constraint simplifies the optimisation problem significantly, the linearisation is only valid for small displacements and/or smooth images.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] To avoid this problem, a multi-scale or coarse-to-fine approach is often used.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] In such a scheme, the images are initially downsampled and the linearised Euler-Lagrange equations are solved at the reduced resolution.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] The estimated flow field at this scale is then used to initialise the process at next scale.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] This initialisation process is often performed by warping one frame using the current estimate of flow field so that it is as similar to other as possible.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] An alternate approach is to discretize the optimisation problem and then perform a search of the possible $(u,v)$ values without linearising it.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] This search is often performed using Max-flow min-cut theorem algorithms, linear programming or belief propagation methods.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] These regularized methods typically require manual tuning of the Lagrange multiplier, the so-called regularization parameters.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] There has been some progress in the automatic determination of these parameters in the context of optical flow applied to particle image velocimetry (PIV) data.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Instead of applying the regularization constraint on a point by point basis as per a regularized model, one can group pixels into regions and estimate the motion of these regions.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] This is known as a *parametric model*, since the motion of these regions is parameterized.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] In formulating optical flow estimation in this way, one makes the assumption that the motion field in each region be fully characterised by a set of parameters.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] The simplest parametric model is the Lucas-Kanade method.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] This uses rectangular regions and parameterises the motion as purely translational.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] The Lucas-Kanade method uses the original brightness constancy constraint as the data cost term and selects $g(x,y)=1$ .
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Other possible local loss functions include the negative normalized cross-correlation between the two frames.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Instead of seeking to model optical flow directly, one can train a machine learning system to estimate optical flow.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Since 2015, when FlowNet was proposed, learning based models have been applied to optical flow and have gained prominence.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] However, with the advent of transformer architecture in 2017, transformer based models have gained prominence.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] A significant shift occurred with the introduction of RAFT (Recurrent All-Pairs Field Transforms), which replaced coarse-to-fine pyramids with a single GRU-based state that iteratively updates the flow field.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] By maintaining a constant feature resolution at 1/8 of the input, RAFT significantly improved the preservation of fine details and robustness to fast motion compared to previous bottleneck-heavy designs, influencing a wide range of subsequent models that adopt similar iterative update mechanisms.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] However, the all-pairs correlation used in such models is computationally expensive; for high-resolution content like FullHD or 4K, global matching can require more than 32 GB of VRAM, making it impractical for consumer-grade GPUs.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] To address this, efficiency-focused methods such as Flow1D, MeFlow, and Memfof have been developed.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] While these approaches generally optimize memory usage by decomposing the 2D search space, the latter optimizes correlation volumes for high-resolution multi-frame sequences, providing a practical implementation for standard GPUs.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Most learning-based approaches to optical flow use supervised learning.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] In this case, many frame pairs of video data and their corresponding ground-truth flow fields are used to optimise the parameters of the learning-based model to accurately estimate optical flow.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] This process often relies on vast synthetic training datasets, such as FlyingChairs and FlyingThings3D, due to the number of parameters involved.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] The models are then evaluated on benchmarks like MPI Sintel, KITTI, and the high-resolution Spring dataset.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] However, models trained exclusively on synthetic data often struggle with the domain gap when applied to real-world footage.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] To address this, some learning-based optical flow approaches use self-supervised learning (sometimes called unsupervised learning) to reduce the need for large datasets with ground-truth data and leverage real-world footage without labels during training.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Instead of training models to minimise the differences between estimated and ground-truth flow fields, they are trained to achieve learning objectives such as brightness constancy and smoothness of the flow field.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] More recently, methods like CroCo have introduced cross-view completion pre-training.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Forcing the network to predict the masked regions of one image using the full second image teaches the model a strong geometric understanding and better generalization than models trained solely on task-specific labels.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Motion estimation and video compression have developed as a major aspect of optical flow research.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Optical flow was used by robotics researchers in many areas such as: object detection and tracking, image dominant plane extraction, movement detection, robot navigation and visual odometry.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Optical flow information has been recognized as being useful for controlling micro air vehicles.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] The application of optical flow includes the problem of inferring not only the motion of the observer and objects in the scene, but also the structure of objects and the environment.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Since awareness of motion and the generation of mental maps of the structure of our environment are critical components of animal (and human) vision, the conversion of this innate ability to a computer capability is similarly crucial in the field of machine vision.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Consider a five-frame clip of a ball moving from the bottom left of a field of vision, to the top right.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Motion estimation techniques can determine that on a two dimensional plane the ball is moving up and to the right and vectors describing this motion can be extracted from the sequence of frames.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] For the purposes of video compression (e.g., MPEG), the sequence is now described as well as it needs to be.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] However, in the field of machine vision, the question of whether the ball is moving to the right or if the observer is moving to the left is unknowable yet critical information.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Not even if a static, patterned background were present in the five frames, could we confidently state that the ball was moving to the right, because the pattern might have an infinite distance to the observer.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Optical flow has also been applied to fluid mechanics as a method of estimating flow patterns in a non-invasive way if visible tracer particles are added.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] This approach is called particle image velocimetry (PIV).
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] It has been shown that optical flow methods can provide higher accuracy than traditional cross-correlation in PIV processing .
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Various configurations of optical flow sensors exist.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] One configuration is an image sensor chip connected to a processor programmed to run an optical flow algorithm.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Another configuration uses a vision chip, which is an integrated circuit having both the image sensor and the processor on the same die, allowing for a compact implementation.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] An example of this is a generic optical mouse sensor used in an optical mouse.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] In some cases the processing circuitry may be implemented using analog or mixed-signal circuits to enable fast optical flow computation using minimal current consumption.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] One area of contemporary research is the use of neuromorphic engineering techniques to implement circuits that respond to optical flow, and thus may be appropriate for use in an optical flow sensor.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Such circuits may draw inspiration from biological neural circuitry that similarly responds to optical flow.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Optical flow sensors are used extensively in computer optical mice, as the main sensing component for measuring the motion of the mouse across a surface.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Optical flow sensors are also being used in robotics applications, primarily where there is a need to measure visual motion or relative motion between the robot and other objects in the vicinity of the robot.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] The use of optical flow sensors in unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs), for stability and obstacle avoidance, is also an area of current research.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] As early as Euclid's *Optics* note was made of the geometry underlying optic flow.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Helmholtz's nineteenth-century account of motion parallax also implicitly concerns it.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] However, its explicit identification arose during the Second World War due the need to understand how pilots judge height and direction during landing.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] MacCurdy, in advise to the Royal Air Force in the late 1920s, had earlier observed that during a straight descent the point on the ground being approached stays fixed in the pilot's visual field while all other points appear to stream away from it.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Grindley, in a classified 1942 report then mathematically analyzed how retinal velocity changed during self-motion to enable an individual to accurately estimate visual speed.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] He, however, considered only this as a cue to altitude and not information to determine travel.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Army Air Forces, first identified that retinal velocities radiate from a "focus of expansion" in the direction of travel.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Moreover, that eye movements do not disturb this, and that it was the global pattern—not individual velocities—that provided this information.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] In 1947, he published the theory, and in 1950 gave the phenomenon the name "optic flow".
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] In 1955, he together with Paul Olum and Frank Rosenblatt detailed its mathematics.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Calvert at the Royal Aircraft Establishment came to a similar ideas when researching on airport approach lighting.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] In 1949, he proposed them as the "parafoveal streamer theory" which described how pilots use the pattern and speed of visual streamers to control their descent.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Gibson stressed the importance of optic flow for affordance perception, the ability to discern possibilities for action within the environment.
[src:mediapipe/optical-flow] Followers of Gibson and his ecological approach to psychology have further demonstrated the role of the optical flow stimulus for the perception of movement by the observer in the world; perception of the shape, distance and movement of objects in the world; and the control of locomotion.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] In the fields of computing and computer vision, **pose** (or **spatial pose**) represents the position and the orientation of an object, each usually in three dimensions.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] Poses are often stored internally as transformation matrices.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] The term “pose” is largely synonymous with the term “transform”, but a transform may often include scale, whereas pose does not.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] In computer vision, the pose of an object is often estimated from camera input by the process of *pose estimation*.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] This information can then be used, for example, to allow a robot to manipulate an object or to avoid moving into the object based on its perceived position and orientation in the environment.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] Other applications include skeletal action recognition.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] The specific task of determining the pose of an object in an image (or stereo images, image sequence) is referred to as *pose estimation*.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] Pose estimation problems can be solved in different ways depending on the image sensor configuration, and choice of methodology.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] Camera resectioning is the process of estimating the parameters of a pinhole camera model approximating the camera that produced a given photograph or video; it determines which incoming light ray is associated with each pixel on the resulting image.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] Basically, the process determines the pose of the pinhole camera.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] Usually, the camera parameters are represented in a 3 × 4 projection matrix called the *camera matrix*.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] The extrinsic parameters define the camera *pose* (position and orientation) while the intrinsic parameters specify the camera image format (focal length, pixel size, and image origin).
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] This process is often called geometric camera calibration or simply camera calibration, although that term may also refer to photometric camera calibration or be restricted for the estimation of the intrinsic parameters only.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] Exterior orientation and interior orientation refer to the determination of only the extrinsic and intrinsic parameters, respectively.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] The classic camera calibration requires special objects in the scene, which is not required in *camera auto-calibration*.
[src:mediapipe/pose-computer-vision] Camera resectioning is often used in the application of stereo vision where the camera projection matrices of two cameras are used to calculate the 3D world coordinates of a point viewed by both cameras.
